Rejects any `#[allow(...)]` attribute in Rust source files tracked by git, failing the check if any are found. Permitted locations: none in MVP. Tests cannot use `#[allow]` — clippy configuration provides `unwrap`/`expect` exceptions instead.

The check inspects files via `git ls-files` (tracked and untracked-but-not-ignored), never a filesystem walk, to avoid descending into `target/` and racing concurrent writers. Uses `grep -nE` to match both `#[allow(...)]` and `#![allow(...)]` at any indentation, with an empty `/dev/null` argument appended to force grep to output `file:line:` prefixes even for a single file, meeting ctx-verify's `split_loc` parser contract.

The `FAIL` exit code signals ctx-verify where the first `FAIL:` line appears; subsequent `FAIL:` lines are parsed as additional violations. Each violation message appends guidance after the matched line to explain why suppressions are banned.